474
51:40.200 --> 51:46.200
an approximation to the statement. There are different
notions of approximation that one might be interested in

475
51:46.200 --> 51:52.320
and we'll see a couple
of them in the third unit of the series, but for these different
notions of approximation,

476
51:52.320 --> 52:00.900
there are quantitative statements
of the no-cloning theorem that put strong limits on how well you can approximately clone.

477
52:00.900 --> 52:07.830
A second remark is that copying or cloning standard basis states most
certainly is possible.

478
52:07.830 --> 52:13.770
For example, a Controlled NOT gate copies the standard basis states of a Qubit.

479
52:13.770 --> 52:21.000
This doesn't contradict
the no-cloning theorem. The point is that cloning in the sense of the no-cloning theorem requires
that this works not only

480
52:21.000 --> 52:24.450
for standard basis states
but for all states.

481
52:24.450 --> 52:29.550
A Controlled NOT gate
certainly doesn't clone a plus state for instance.

482
52:29.550 --> 52:35.790
And finally, it is worth pointing out that there's also a no-cloning theorem for
probabilistic states.

483
52:35.790 --> 52:39.870
It's just not something
that people talk about or care about.

484
52:39.870 --> 52:47.520
If somebody randomly
chooses a bit, for instance, for some arbitrary way of
assigning probabilities to the two values and
then hands you that bit,

485
52:47.520 --> 52:52.440
of course there's no way for you to obtain two independent samples
of that random bit.

486
52:52.440 --> 52:55.500
You just don't know what
the probabilities are.

487
52:55.500 --> 53:03.390
You can copy the bit just like a Controlled NOT
copies standard basis states, but that's not the same thing as cloning the probabilistic state.

488
53:03.390 --> 53:08.970
You just don't have enough
information to do that. Whatever random bit you were given doesn't tell you what
the probabilities were.

489
53:08.970 --> 53:12.000
It's just a bit.

490
53:12.000 --> 53:17.610
The impossibility of cloning
a probabilistic state follows from exactly the same reasoning as in the quantum setting.

491
53:17.610 --> 53:25.980
Cloning is a non-linear process, whereas probabilistic operations, just like unitary operations, are linear.

492
53:25.980 --> 53:33.120
Anyway, it's not surprising
that we can't clone on a probabilistic state and
somehow it's not as interesting as the fact that we can't
clone a quantum state,

493
53:33.120 --> 53:38.250
but the point is simply to observe that this is not a uniquely
quantum phenomenon.

494
53:38.250 --> 53:44.850
The final limitation
of quantum information that we'll discuss in this lesson is that it's not possible
to perfectly discriminate

495
53:44.850 --> 53:48.570
two quantum states that aren't orthogonal.

496
53:48.570 --> 53:55.950
Another way of saying this
is that if two quantum states can be perfectly discriminated, then they have to be orthogonal.

497
53:55.950 --> 54:03.600
What we mean when we refer
to a perfect discrimination of two quantum states, Psi and Phi, is that there's some
way to tell them apart

498
54:03.600 --> 54:06.750
without any chance of error.

499
54:06.750 --> 54:13.320
In terms of the quantum circuit model, we can express this as you
see here on the screen.

500
54:13.320 --> 54:20.130
We have some unitary operation U, which could be implemented
as a quantum circuit or we could just think about U abstractly

501
54:20.130 --> 54:26.670
as a unitary operation
and force input U takes either the state Psi or the state Phi

502
54:26.670 --> 54:34.500
along with a bunch of initialized Qubits, which you can think of as workspace Qubits that somehow assist in this
process of discrimination.

503
54:34.500 --> 54:42.510
After U as applied, the top Qubit is measured with respect to a standard basis measurement and here's the perfect
discrimination part.

504
54:42.510 --> 54:49.500
If the input state was Psi, then the measurement must
give the outcome zero, 100% of the time, and if
the input state was Phi,

505
54:49.500 --> 54:54.900
then the measurement must
give the outcome one, again with 100% chance.

506
54:54.900 --> 54:59.160
It's not important what the
states of these other Qubits are after U was applied.

507
54:59.160 --> 55:07.710
All that matters is this one bit that we get from the measurement because that's the bit that's telling us which of the two states we started with.

508
55:07.710 --> 55:15.210
For some choices of states, Psi and Phi, it will be possible to perform a perfect discrimination like
this and for others it won't.

509
55:15.210 --> 55:21.417
And what we'll observe is that
if it is possible to do this, then Psi and Phi have
to be orthogonal states

510
55:21.417 --> 55:28.530
and that means if Phi and
Psi are not orthogonal, you can't perfectly discriminate them.

511
55:28.530 --> 55:33.900
So let's see why a perfect discrimination implies orthogonality.

512
55:33.900 --> 55:39.630
We'll start by writing down two equations that express what these
two diagrams express.

513
55:39.630 --> 55:46.380
If we think about the quantum state, we get after applying U to a
bunch of initialized Qubits together with the state Psi,

514
55:46.380 --> 55:54.180
we see that it has to
have this form right here, where Pi zero is some quantum state vector representing the state
of all of these Qubits

515
55:54.180 --> 56:01.950
except for the top one. We don't have any information
about this quantum state, Pi zero, it could be anything,

516
56:01.950 --> 56:11.580
but we know that the entire
state has to look like this because that's the only
way that the measurement is guaranteed to give the
outcome zero, 100% of the time.

517
56:11.580 --> 56:14.970
And we have an analogous
equation for the second one.

518
56:14.970 --> 56:21.120
This time the top Qubit
has to be in the one state and similar to Pi zero, the
state Pi one could be anything.

519
56:21.120 --> 56:28.350
And in addition to having
no information about Pi one, we also don't know anything
about the relationship between Pi zero and Pi one.

520
56:28.350 --> 56:33.540
For all we know, these are just two
arbitrary quantum states.

